Nice!  That's a good idea.  Now that you point it out I obviously should have implemented it this way in the first place :/

Anyway, I looked over the code and I think I see a problem.  The memory buffers need to be more than just thread_local, since you can switch the active cuda device in a thread.  If you just grab the thread local buffer you might end up with a buffer on the wrong GPU device.  You should be able to deal with this problem with the pattern I use for the cudnn context object: https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/dlib/dnn/cudnn_dlibapi.cpp#L115

In particular, imagine there was a class like this:
```
class resizable_buffer
{  public:
   cuda_data_void_ptr get(size_t size);
   /* returns a pointer to at least size bytes, will reallocate the underlying buffer if necessary.  
      Importantly, cuda_data_void_ptr tracks if anyone is still using memory from a previous 
      call to get(), so when/if we do a reallocation we don't free any memory buffer being used. 
 
      The idea here is that you don't store the output of get() anywhere other than locally in
      a function.  That is, you call get() each time you need the buffer for a call to cuDNN. */
  private: 
    cuda_data_void_ptr buffer; // get() just returns this, if it's big enough, otherwise it reallocates.
};

static std::shared_ptr<resizable_buffer> device_global_buffer(); 
```

`device_global_buffer` could be implemented similarly to how the cudnn context() method I mentioned works.  You call device_global_buffer to get the global resizable_buffer appropriate for your thread and device.  You also store the shared_ptr<resizable_buffer> as a private member of the tensor_conv so that once all the tensor_conv's are destroyed the resizable_buffer is freed (this assumes you use weak_ptrs inside the device_global_buffer implementation). 

As an aside, you can use the dlib::cuda::cuda_data_void_ptr to allocate GPU buffers, rather than dealing with the CUDA C API directly.

