You would have to implement your own callback. You can't use the on that comes with Keras because keras_rl doesn't have epochs. The interface for the keras_rl Callback looks like so

```
class Callback(KerasCallback):
    def _set_env(self, env):
        self.env = env

    def on_episode_begin(self, episode, logs={}):
        pass

    def on_episode_end(self, episode, logs={}):
        pass

    def on_step_begin(self, step, logs={}):
        pass

    def on_step_end(self, step, logs={}):
        pass

    def on_action_begin(self, action, logs={}):
        pass

    def on_action_end(self, action, logs={}):
        pass
```
You would probably want to save your model at the end of each episode and keep the one with best total reward over all previous episodes. I imagine you could also extract some code from the Keras [ModelCheckPoint Callback](https://github.com/keras-team/keras/blob/master/keras/callbacks.py).
